-------------------
Before VM and Containers
one applications running per server, so multiple servers for a single company and
since the hardware requierements weren't known before building the app,
the servers were bought after some guessing, so often too powerful just in case, wasting money

VM and VMware and VMwarts
VM share the same hardware, each VM has it's own kernel, so can mix Debian and Windows on same hardware
They solved the issue of dedicating a server for an app
Since each VM has a dedicated OS that consumes CPU and RAM resources, it still isn't the optimal solution
Because of that, they are slower and not very portable

Containers
No need for a full OS for each containers, they share the host's one
So it's less resources allocated per container
They're faster, more portable and easier to maintain
Since containers share the same kernel, some containers can't be on the same machine as other
So there are 2 types of containers: Linux containers and Windows containers

Docker
Before Docker, containers weren't available to most companies outside those who worked on it
Docker allow containers to be accessible

Docker technology: runtime, deamon, orchestrator

